Preheat your oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Remove the @lamb steaks{2} from your fridge to allow them to come up to room temperature. Bring a large #saucepan{} of water with @salt{1/2%tsp} to the boil for the potatoes.

Chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2cm chunks (peel first if you prefer). Peel the @garlic cloves{2}.

When boiling, add the potatoes and garlic to the water and cook until you can easily slip a knife through the potatoes, ~{15-20%minutes}.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of oil in a large #frying pan{} on high heat.

Season the steaks with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}. > TIP: Lamb steaks naturally vary in shape, so adjust the following timings depending on how you like yours cooked.

Once hot, lay the steaks into the pan and fry until browned and medium-rare, ~{8-10%minutes} total. Turn every ~{2%minutes}. > TIP: Cook each side for 1-2 min more if you like it more well done. IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat.

Meanwhile, bring another medium saucepan of water to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp} for the green beans.

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @echalion shallot{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced). Trim the @green beans{150%g}(trimmed).

When the water is boiling, add the beans and cook until just tender, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{}, then return to the saucepan. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Toss in @olive oil{}.

Once the lamb is cooked, transfer to a #board{}, cover with #foil{} and allow to rest for a couple of mins. > IMPORTANT: The lamb is safe to eat when browned on the outside.

Pop your (now empty) frying pan back on medium heat with a drizzle of oil. Once hot, add the shallot and fry until softened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add the @balsamic vinegar{12%ml} and cook until almost evaporated, then add the @fig jam{40%g}, @chicken stock paste{10%g} and @water{150%ml} for the sauce (see pantry for amount). Bring to the boil and simmer until the sauce has thickened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Remove from the heat.

Once the potatoes and garlic are cooked, drain in a colander and return to the pan, off the heat. Add a knob of @butter{1%knob} and a splash of @milk{}(splash) (if you have any) and mash with a #potato masher{} until smooth.

Stir through the @Parmigiano Reggiano{20%g} until melted. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cover with a #lid{} to keep warm.

When everything's almost ready, reheat the fig sauce if needed.

Share the cheesy garlic mash between your plates. Thinly slice the lamb and serve on top of the mash.

Spoon the balsamic fig sauce over the lamb.

Serve the green beans alongside and sprinkle the beans with the @toasted flaked almonds{15%g} to finish.

Enjoy!